	"conclusion": "For Intercom, the career page strongly precedes Linkedin: 83% of matched jobs (29/35) appeared on the career page first, with an average lead of 362 days (median: 379 days). An additional 130 jobs (79% of career-page listings) were never indexed by Linkedin at all. This confirms that the career page is the primary source of truth for job postings.",
	"geminiSummary": "Analysis of Intercom's job posting patterns reveals a significant and consistent lead for the company's career page over LinkedIn. Of the 35 job postings identified on both platforms, 29 (83%) appeared first on Intercom's career page. This pre-publication advantage is substantial, with an average lag of 362 days and a median lag of 379 days, meaning jobs are typically posted on the company's internal page nearly a year before appearing on LinkedIn. Only four jobs were observed first on LinkedIn, with two appearing on the same day across both platforms, underscoring the career page's dominant role as the initial publication channel.\n\nThe distribution of these lags highlights the profound advantage for those monitoring the career page directly. While 5 jobs showed a relatively short lead of 1–3 days and 2 jobs within 31–60 days, the vast majority—22 jobs—exhibited a lag of 90 days or more. This substantial cluster of long delays means that for most matched positions, job seekers accessing Intercom's career page would discover opportunities many months, or even over a year, ahead of their public appearance on LinkedIn. Prominent examples, such as \"Senior Product Designer\" and \"Technical Recruiter,\" showed leads exceeding 750 days, demonstrating that the career page frequently serves as the exclusive initial platform for highly sought-after roles for extended periods.\n\nIt is important to acknowledge certain caveats regarding this analysis. The study focused on a single company, Intercom, limiting generalizability to the broader labor market without further research. Furthermore, the discrepancy in data collection frequency, with 200 career page snapshots versus only 6 LinkedIn snapshots over the analysis period (2024-01-01 to 2026-04-01), could potentially inflate the observed lag. A more frequent LinkedIn crawl might identify some jobs earlier, although the sheer magnitude of the average and median lags, along with the numerous jobs appearing 90+ days earlier, strongly suggests a fundamental difference in publication strategy rather than just an artifact of snapshot frequency. Additionally, 130 unique jobs were found exclusively on Intercom's career page, indicating that a significant portion of roles may never be cross-posted to LinkedIn, at least not within the analyzed timeframe.\n\nFor job seekers, this data offers a clear and actionable recommendation: consistently monitoring company career pages directly is critical for gaining a competitive edge. Doing so for companies like Intercom can provide access to new job postings days, weeks, or even many months, and in some cases over a year, before they are advertised on broader platforms like LinkedIn. This strategy not only offers a significant head start in the application process but also uncovers roles that may never be syndicated to third-party job boards, effectively broadening a job seeker's pool of potential opportunities.",
